column17: Santa Barbara Airlines Cargo/Diamond Air Freight Inc
column168: AWB 249-12370923 was tendered to Diamond Air Freight (cargo handling agents for Santa Barbara Airlines Cargo) on May 2, 2007, for transportation on a passenger aircraft to Caracas, Venezuela, on May 3, 2007.    AWB consisted of six plastic bags declared as "Courier Bags." Upon screening of the freight prior to loading unto aircraft, as required by the Transportation Security Administration (TSA), we found undeclared dangerous goods in one bag. The bag contained a single carton box with the following: 1) about 40 maritime emergency air flares kits consisting of a pistol and 4 cartridges; 2) about 120 4-cartridge packages; 3) 5 kits containing a pistol, cartridges, hand flares, and a radio-signaling device. Items on number 3 were marked as UN0373 and 1.4G, all other items were displayed as flammable, but had no information on the specific hazmat classification.    The shipment was automatically put on hold and reported to FAA. The shipper and consignee on the house AWB are:    Shipper:  MAKI Express  4095 SW 137 Ave Suite #11  Miami, FL 33175  USA    Consignee:  El Capitan Centro Nautico  C/C Bello Campo Local 52  Altamira, Caracas  VENEZUELA    The house AWB was declared as "partes" (spanish for "parts") and consisted of 2 pieces, 82 kg.

column168: TAG (The Adherence Group) performed an inspection on this shipment and discovered a boxed motorcycle with a carton of battery acid contained in the shipment.  The carton was marked with the corrosive label.  This motorcycle was shipped from Europe and was not declared under the UN3166 entry.  The shipment was held pending the receipt of corrected documentation.  There was no release of cargo and no spill.
column169: Motorcycle and vehicles shipped from outside of the US create a lot of problems when the shipment is then exported to offshore US locations like Alaska and Hawaii by water.  It would be good if vehicles, UN3166,  could be harmonized with the IMDG regulations.  The shipper need training on flagging these type of differences in the regulations.

column168: At 0915 hours, 05/03/2007, the CSX Trasportation (CSXT), Eastbound Yardmaster, Willard Terminal, Willard, OH advised T. J. Mannas, Mgr. - Hazmat Field Services, CSXT, Willard, OH, that he had received a report of a odor about Eatbound Class 12 track. T. J. Mannas inspected the cars on this track and noted evidence of liquid release on "BR" side of tank. No material evident on tracks (ground). Liquid  was noted atop ACFX 72189 on "BR" side of manway nozzle and emanating from the manway nozzle and its cover. One of six manway cover bolsts (bolt immediately to the right of the manway cover hinge) was less than hand tight. Eagle Construction and Environmental Services, Inc. (ECESI), Findlay, OH responded and  broke seals "033505" on "R" side manway cover safety bolt and "032942" on the "L" side manway cover safety bolt. Outage was below indicator ("T bar"). ECESI replaced the manway cover gasket and secured the tank car. All other fittings were inspected with no further evidence of release. The bottom outlet auxiliary valve was equipped with a 90 degree elbow connection. The closure for the nipple at the end of  this elbowed connection was a cap. The cap was not affixed to the tank. ECESI removed the elbowed connected, at the direction of the car owner, GE Rail Car, and secured the plug, which was affixed to a chain,  into the auxiliary valve.T. J. Mannas advised Mr. Jon Hall, Plant Manager, Zaclon, Inc., Cleveland, OH of this.     Cause Code:  200  NARRI:  5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: Drums were tendered to carrier on pallets.  Pallets were loaded in nose of trailer without incident.  The dockworker load the trailer then placed dunnage skids behind the drums to protect them from damage by other freight that would have been loaded on trailer.  As dockworker was loading additional freight, his forks protruded through the dunnage skids, puncturing one drum.  Damage was immediately noticed, and drum was placed on its side to stop the leak.  Approximately 2 quarts of product was released.  Spill was contained and cleaned up with absorbent compound.  Damaged drum was placed in haz mat bay for handling.
column169: Dock worker will be counseled and retrained.  Specific use of empty pallets as dunnage will be examined and retraining on that subject will be held with all employees.  Shipment was packaged adequately for transport as received from the manufacturer.

column18: JFK Airport, Bldg 23, Cargo Area B
column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at the facility, one fiber board drum was punctured by the shrink wrap machine.  Approximately 5 kilograms of free product were released.  The New York Port Authority responded to assess the site.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. of Mount Arlington, New Jersey was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. recovered the free product and placed the damaged fiber board drum into a 55-gallon overpack drum.  One, 30-gallon drum of waste was generated as a result of the incident and was transported by H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. to their facility in Mount Arlington, New Jersey pending disposal coordination.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and may have been related to a puncture by the shrink wrap machine, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Alliance Airlines will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: During a routine TAG inspection to determine shipping paper description against the actual shipment, 18 cartons of hazardous product listed and labeled UN3266 was discovered in the container shipment.  The container was not placarded nor was the hazardous cargo listed on the hazmat documentation.  The shipper was notified and the shipment was held until corrected documentation was received and placards applied to the ocean container.
column169: Better hazmat training is required for those shippers who infrequently ship hazardous cargo.

column168: Our truck was traveling west on HWY 174 in a A-Train cofiguration.  The conditions were very wind with heavy gusts.  The road is a narrow two lane road with very soft shoulders.  A large gust of wind pushed the lead trailer off the shoulder with the pup trailer following.  The driver corrected and brought the semi back up on the road however the pup trailer turned on its right side.  The trailer slide for appoximatley 300ft while the driver was slowing the vehicle.  The right side of the trailer sustained damage which breeched the tank realeasing the product on the side of the highway.  There were approximately four openings on the vessel appoximately 3 to 6 inches long and 1 inch wide.  The local Sheriffs department was called and responded.  Company incident management team responded.  Hazardous material clean up company, USA Enviromental LLC responded.  Central Utah Public Health Department responded.  The realease took approximately 20 minutes.  The release was contained in a small area with efforts from the driver diking the product with exsisting dirt.
column169: On May 15th we had a company safety meeting going over the incident.  We talked about the dangers of this particular road and other frequent roads we travel that could be a risk.  We idenified the dangers of soft shoulders and windy conditions.  We talked about decreasing speeds below the posted speed limit on these roads.

column168: On 05/06/07 at 18:00 hrs., tank car UTLX220965, load Hydrogen Peroxide, Aqueous Solution, was reported leaking from the top of car.  The car was isolated and a CSXT emergency response contractor,  Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), was dispatched to respond.  Upon arrival, SPSI noted one of the manway cover bolts was less than hand tight. SPSI noted the seal for the "bread box" was intact but they could remove the securement pin for the "bread box" without compromising the integrity of the seal. SPSI noted three of four securement bolts for the liquid line blind closure flange were less than finger tight with the fourth bolt being merely hand tight. A ratchet, socket and crescent wrench were found under the "bread box" by SPSI. Ratchet was stenciled "GRAY-CANADA" and the socket was stenciled "UTILITY." While insuring the plug for the air line valve was tool tight with a 2' pipe wrench, SPSI advised the air line valve freely turned 2.5 full turns on its nipple. The shipper was notifed. The car is being held until shipper obtains FRA Movement Approval or a leak test in accord with U. S. DOT Regulations is sucessfully completed.     Cause Code:  242  NARRI:  5(5+3+1) x (2+0) = 90

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred. While loading, one 55 gallons drum was punctured resulting in the release of approximately 1/2 gallon of product. H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. of Linden, New Jersey was contacted to perform cleanup. H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. performed cleanup using PPE and speedy dry. The cleanup and spent materials were placed into one fifty-five gallon drum pending disposal. The affected drum was overpacked and will be forwarded to the consignee. H.M.H.T.T.C. Response, Inc. will handle disposal coordination of the waste generated from this incident. No injuries or exposures were reported. The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Alliance Airlines personnel will continue to reinforce safety guidlines and handling proceedures to all personnel.

column168: A random TAG inspection reflected a leak from a carton in the container.  The cause of the leak was obvious.  There were orintation arrows on the cargon indicating the end that was to face up but the liquid corrosive product was loaded upside down leaking product from the carton onto the floor of the container.  The shipper was notified, the container placed on hold, a response company dispatched to take care of the leak and the shipment was delayed due to the cleanup mitigation process.
column169: The cause of this spill was for the most part human error coupled with inadequate or no training.  This incident could have been prevented had the loading personnel used common sense in the loading.

column168: A 55 gallon steel removable top drum was overpacked into a removable top 85 gallon drum at the customer's location. The drum was transported to the destination facility without incident. As the vehicle was being off-loaded it was discovered that pressure had built up inside the 85 gallon drum sufficient enough to cause the lid to come off and a spraying of some material was observed within the vehicle. After contacting the shipper, it was learned that the sodium hydroxide solution was used to clean aluminum materials, which is not compatible with the sodium hydroxide. It is believed that the overpacking of the 55 gallon drum agitated some residual aluminum material in the container which then reacted with the sodium hyderoxide to build up pressure until the lid was compromised. The material was then stabilized and recontainerized prior to shipping offsite for disposal.
column169: We have discussed the incident with the shipper. They are currently reviewing their processing procedures and are evaluating alternative chemicals for this process.

column168: When I arrived at the terminal this morning the dispatcher advised me that that we had a leaker.  We identified the problem as a 55 gallon drum on the very end of the trailer 66450. There was a small amount of liquid on the trailer floor and a small amount on the ground.  The drum was overpacked and spill cleaned up with floor dry.

column168: ACFX 77732 was noted by carrier personnel with product dripping from the bottom outlet valve.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco Inc, responded and attempted unsuccessfully to stop the release by tighteneing the valve operating handle.  The drip was slowed but not stopped.    The valve cap was removed, retaped and reinstalled stopping the release.  The cause of the valve leak could not be determined with the car loaded.  The car was moved to the consignees facility under FRA Movement Authority where the valve will be inspected and repaired after unloading.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: GATX 12564 was noted during pre-unloading inspection by consignee personnel with material splashed on the top and sides of the car.    Further inspection revealed the safety vent frangible disc was ruptured.  The disc was replaced to prevent further release.    It is unknown exactly when or where the release originally occurred.  The car was loaded to 99.25 per cent of its capacity by weight indicating the car was overloaded likely contributing to the disc failure.      The spilled material was cleaned from the car and properly disposed of.

column168: TILX 400945 was noted by carrier personnel with product venting continuously from the top of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives responded and found 2 pressure regulators valves frozen open allowing excessive venting of product.    The ice was removed from the valves allowing them to reseat stopping the release.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: During the unloading process, the checker found a skid of boxes containing one gallon plasic bottles of isopropanol solution, leaking. Upon further examination, one box located on the bottom of the stack and directly in contact with the skid had been punctured. Approximately 16 ounces of the solutio  n had spilled into the trailer and the outer packaging of the bottle was wet. I contacted Jason Wing at Ft. Smith and upon his direction I took the following action. No clean up was necessary because the solution of alchol evaporated. I put the leaking bottle into a plastic bag then into a authorize  d recovery drum. The drum was labelled with a copy of the pro # manifest and a flammable hazard label. The skid was re-palletized properly and sent to the consignee with the damaged freight. The freight was placed into a trailer for transport properly blocked / braced.
column169: Ensure that the freight has adequate dunnage between the skid and the freight to prevent a puncture. Ensure freight is properly blocked and braced for transport.

column168: There were nine 5 gallon drums loaded on tail of trailer.  When employee was loading final drum onto trailer the drum struck a skid punctured the side of the drum causing contents to spill out.  Drum was quickly picked up and removed.
column169: Pre-Shift meetings are held on a regular basis at out terminal, in this case, the next day after occurence the pre shift meeting was all about safety and loading procedures on dock and how to prevent an incident like this from happening again

column168: At 1500 driver Oscar Salazar called to report he had a Muratic Acid spill of 2 boxes of 4 x 1 gallon jugs each (4G combination packaging with inner one gallon plastic containers). He attempted to readjust the load when two boxes with four one gallon jugs fell off a pallet onto the flatbed trailer # 3248. Plant manager John Cannon and supervisor Jeff Sanchez arrived and met with Largo Fire Dept Lt Mark Michaels and under the direction of the Fire Dept. began the spill cleanup.  Clean up was completed by 1730.

column25: Bax Global agent for Dow Chemical USA
column168: While loading aircraft pallets from dollies to the loader one ramp worker could not  push pallet by hand. He got a forklift to push the pallet with instead of getting  additional manpower. While using the forklift he put a forklift blade through the metal drum causing the leak. The pallet with leaking material was never on the loader or aircraft as it never left the dollie. The dollie with leaking material was moved away from the immediate area. The Lufthansa agent who was on the aircraft contacted 911 as soon as he saw leakage of material on ramp from the trail left by the dollie being moved. As the ramp agent was keeping people away from the area he did not actually see the holes or damage to the dangerous goods. The DFW fire dept and environmental dept took over the site upon arrival and had several hours of cleanup and containment. The company Cactus Environmental Services did the final removal of the damaged drums(the one that leaked as well as 1 drum dented which the fire dept wanted removed), and other material used in the cleanup (plastic, speedy dry, decam baths).
column169: Not using forklifts to load pallets. This has always been the Lufthansa policy but it has been reinforced with our handeling agent Inergrated Aircraft Services.

column168: 1. Cargo tank MC331 VIKPT retested and inspected by Gas Service & Supply on 4-26-07.  2. The first load on the tank since inspection was 5-15-07 (Butane Mix).  3. While loading, driver observed vapor leaking form front manhole cover.  4. Driver closed all valves and stopped loading.  5. Vapor continued to leak from manhole cover.  6. The Butane Mix was off loaded from leaking trailer to another MC331.  7. The leak stopped and the traile was taken out of service.  8. It was determined several nuts on the lower portion of the manhole were loose.
column169: 1. Gas Service was notified of the incident.  2. The loose nuts on the manhole have been retorqued to manufacturer specifications.  3. The trailer has not been placed back in service pending re-testinf for leaks.

column168: Driver was preparing to transfer product from cargo tank to customer storage tank using pump on tractor.  He had the hoses hooked up and the customer valve open. He opened the valve on the trailer just a little to walk the line to make sure there weren't any problems before he engaged the pump.  When he walked the line back to the trailer, he noticed product coming out of an open petcock on the back of the pump.  He immediately put a bucket under it and closed the valve.  Transfer of product was completed without further incident.  Spill pads were used to clean up the quart spill.
column169: Driver wasn't aware that the new pump that was installed on his tractor had a petcock valve on the back of it and he didn't check to make sure it was closed.  His old pump didn't have a valve there.  He now understands the difference between the two pumps.

column168: The accident occurred on Highway 54 outside of Osceola, MO.  This highway is a two lane non-divided road.  The conditions were clear, and no other vehicles were traveling on the road at the time of the accident.  The driver was traveling westbound on highway 54.  As the vehicle reached a left hand curve the driver failed to negotiate the maneuver.  The trailer’s right front tires went off the right shoulder causing the tractor to go off the right side of the road as well.  Both vehicles struck trees that were lining the road and finally the trailer rolled over on its right hand side.      The Collins Fire Department, Missouri State Highway Patrol, Sunbelt Environmental Services, and an independent adjustor representing Great West Casualty Company all responded to the scene.  The highway was never closed during any time of the clean up process.  The clean up required the load to be off loaded into a relief trailer in order to clear the scene.  Erickson Transport supplied the relief trailer and driver.  Sunbelt Environmental transferred the product by cold tapping the damaged trailer and pumping the product into the relief trailer.  After the transfer was complete it allowed the wrecker service to clear the area of the damaged vehicles.  During the clean up process the Missouri Department of Natural Resources (MDNR) was contacted, their spill number is 070529-1015-CRJ. MDNR did not find it necessary to conduct a further investigation at the scene.  There was no product loss as result of the accident or during the transfer, the only product that was released was eight ounces that was collected in a container placed under the dome lid.       The conclusion of the state highway’s investigation and the independent adjustor’s report ruled the cause of the accident was due to inattention from the driver.  The driver received a citation for failure to maintain present lane.  Due to the circumstances and physical evidence there were no other mitigating factors.  To clarify the response to question 25 there was no failure of the equipment, there was no release of product.  The failure was the drivers action, no mechanical failure occurred.
column169: Due to the cause of the accident all corrective actions deal with education and retraining.  The employment of the driver involved in this accident was terminated because of the results of the investigations and the severity of the accident.     A major part of education and training is our safety meeting.  At the next safety meeting, which will be held in August, this accident will be covered extensively with all drivers from the events leading up to the accident, the damages, root cause and cost incurred.  Another aspect of this accident is the routing, we will discuss with the drivers what they feel is the safest routing and establish that as the desired route for that delivery.  All of this will be done to illustrate to the drivers how their actions directly affect their safety, the safety of others on the road, and the dangers of the job.  We also do this because the drivers are more receptive and learn more when we share problems that their peers may be having.  This also reiterates that situations like this can happen to anyone of them, keeping them from becoming complacent.         Due to the importance of these safety meetings we ensure that the message and discussion is not soon forgotten.  After each meeting a letter is sent out to each driver, no matter if they attended the meeting or not.  This letter reviews the topics discussed and notifies them if there attendance was excused or not.  If a driver is able to attend a meeting due to work restrictions then a individual meeting is arranged with the safety manager.      Each month a handout that is put together by the National Tank Truck Carriers and JJ Keller is distributed to the drivers.  This hand out covers the topic of rollovers every other month, the other months it covers other safety related topics.  Attached to the handout is a quiz which the drivers complete and return to the safety department.  This program prior to the accident was not formalized, however with this accident it will be formally implemented into the safety program.       Finally we will review rollover training that is used during driver orientation.  Presently the drivers watch a video on rollover situations and take a quiz.  We will work with our insurance agent’s safety department to make improvements.  With these changes, education, and keeping this unfortunate incident in front of the drivers we feel that management and the drivers will be able to prevent this type of accident from reoccurring.

column168: Material Spill in Trailer:    NEMF Truck carrying our drums on pallets and farm equipment arrived on our dock with a damaged drum.  Drum appears to have been punctured when the farm equipment shifted in transit and banged against the drums, bending many and puncturing one.  Our shipping and receiving staff noticed the odor and the leaking drum before we handled a drum.  NEMF unloaded drums.    Cleanup:    Very little leaked.  The drum was placed on a containment pallet and the contents were transferred into another container.  No measurable amount of contents was lost.  Absorbent was placed on the trailer bed and swept up.  No measurable amount of contents was absorbed.    Environmental Damage:    A trace amount of the contents evaporated.     No hazardous material reached a waterway, sanitary sewer, storm sewer, or the ground.
column169: This is the second incident in 18 months, with the same players.  Ashland palletized shipments of the drums, but NEMF allowed farm equipment to be placed too close to the drums and the equipment damaged several drums, including puncturing one.    Spartech instituted several measures that help eliminate human exposure and limit environmental exposure.  Spill kits, including the containment pallet was available at the dock.  Employees had been trained and reacted properly in a timely fashion.    Spartech is contacting NEMF and Ashland to discuss corrective action on their parts.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Highway 60, just west of Seiling, Oklahoma, the Exide Technologies driver lost control of the vehicle, which caused the truck to rollover into the embankment.  The tractor-trailer unit was hauling 538 batteries at the time of the incident.  Approximately 50 gallons of battery acid were released.  The Oklahoma Department of Environmental Quality, Oklahoma Department of Transportation, Oklahoma Highway Patrol, Woodward Fire Department, and Mooreland Fire Department responded to the site.  Boomer Environmental of Midwest City, Oklahoma was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Boomer Environmental offloaded some of the damaged batteries from the trailer, in an effort to assist the Wrecking Company in removing the vehicle from the embankment.  Upon uprighting the damaged vehicle, Boomer Environmental neutralized the free product on the affected roadway, and began to excavate the impacted soils from the embankment and road shoulder.  Boomer Environmental also proceeded to offload all batteries, deconned, shrink-wrapped, and repalletized.  Disposition was coordinated directly by Exide Technologies.  The contaminated soil, debris, and neutralized product were placed into a rolloff box, which were transported for disposal, in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.  Oklahoma Department of Environmental Quality oversaw cleanup activity, and site was cleared for closure.  No further action is required.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Exide Technologies will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel

column168: I recieved a call from a company driver stating that during his first check of the load, he smelled somthing that reminded him of SBS 38%.  He then checked the 3 IBC's of SBS 38% on his truck and noticed that the IBC in question appeared to have started to weep some product as the bottom of the packaging had a small amount of material in the sump of the bin.  I contacted another company driver that was close by and we decided that since the bin was not leaking, but rather weeping, we could transport back to the branch as the truck was within 40 miles.  The drivers had estimated less than a gallon was in the bottom of the IBC when the truck arrived back at the branch.  The IBC was placed in our portable IBC recovery area until we were able to empty the bin.  We weighted the IBC and based on the weight, the IBC had leaked a total of 6 gallons of material from the time the driver discovered the situation until we weighted the bin, some 4 hours later.  The truck was loaded and secured as policy states and was not weeping when the load was checked before the driver left the branch.  After we unloaded the IBC, we found that a small stress crack had developed on the bottom of the bin.  The IBC was taken out of service by the testing branch.
column169: After an investigation was completed, we felt as if the IBC developed a stress crack as result of age.  The Corporate policy was to purchase a more expensive, higher quality IBC for select products and that has been quite sucessful, since implimented last year. Based on this incident, during the next conference call, a decision will be made on the continued use of the Claswon IBC's we have in service for other hazardous materials such as SBS 38%. The IBC in question passed the required DOT testing requirement a month before this incident.  Based on pass records, the Clawon IBC's have been reliable and we had few incidents with them as result of age but rather most issues were due to the treatment and storage.

column168: AT 18:35 LEE BARTON WAS LOADING TRAILER #621036. AS LEE PICKED UP THE PACKAGE IT BURST INTO FLAMES. LARAME DAVIS (HAZ MAT RESPONDER) PUT OUT THE FIRE WITH AN EXTINGUISHER. JAMES GLOVER HIT THE EMERGENCY EVACUATION ALARM. LORI DAVIS AND JONATHAN OSULLIVAN STARTED MOVING PEOPLE OUT OF THE BLDG. AT 18:40 CITY POLICE OFFICER ARRIVED. I WAS TOLD TO HAVE NICK JONES PULL THE TRAILER OFF THE WALL BY THE FIRE DEPT. AT 18:50 THE FIRE DEPT WENT INSIDE THE TRAILER TO INVESTIGATE THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 2 GAS REGULATORS THAT WAS LEAKING GASOLINE. THE FIRE FIGHTER EXPLAINED THAT BOTH WERE WRAPPED IN PLASTIC. THE GASOLINE GOT INTO THE PLASTIC WITH THE POWER BOX AND CREATED AN ELECTRIC STATIC SPARK THAT IGNITED THE PACKAGE. IT IS NOT KNOWN WHETHER OR NOT THIS PACKAGE SHOULD HAVE BEEN A DECLARED HAZMAT PACKAGE.

Our driver, David Parlapiano, related that he was filling one of the last cylinders in the storage cage outside the concrete building when the cylider fill valve did not seat properly as he was disconnecting. He disconnected and attempted to re-connect to charge the cylinder and re-seat the valve. A flash fire engulfed him. He backed away, rolled on the asphalt, got the fire extinguisher and put out the flame on the forklift cylinder. There was no apparent source of ignition. We are doing our own investigation. The driver handled the situation in a very professional and courageous manner. There apparently was only an incidental release of propane from the stickly fill valve.
column169: At this point, we are considering this a freak accident since there was no known source of ignition. Our insurance carrier suggested that the source of ignition was static electricity. We are considering future recommedations.

column168: Our driver pulled up to the customer’s carbon dioxide tank to fill it from his truck mounted tank. He unloaded the fill hose and connected it to the outlet connection on the truck mounted tank and the inlet connection on the customer’s tank. He was assisted by another driver in the filling process. When the driver who was assisting in the fill process opened the valve on the truck mounted tank to begin filling the customer’s tank the hose separated from the inlet connection on the customer’s tank and vented the liquid C02 from the truck mounted tank. The truck mounted tank was allowed to empty completely due to the fact that the fill hose was gyrating in an uncontrolled manner which made it unsafe to approach the shut off valve for the truck mounted tank until the pressure was reduced in the truck mounted tank sufficiently to close the shut off valve. The failure occurred at the point of connection on the customer’s tank. Our follow up investigation was inconclusive as to the exact cause of the failure.
column169: We have performed additional training and reviewed proper filling procedures with particular emphasis on secure fill hose/tank connections with the driver involved. In addition we have installed “anti-whip” hose restraints on all fill hoses.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While in the process of unloading a shipment of thirty-two (32), fifty-five (55) gallon drums a leak was noticed from one (1) drum.  Approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product were released.  Wilson Trucking Corporation personnel contained and performed cleanup  by placing down four and half (4.5), fourty (40) pound bags of speedy dry and swept up the waste into one (1), twenty (20) gallon hazmat container.  All waste generated will be disposed of internally. The remaining freight was forwarded to the consignee.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental and appears to have been due to an unknown occurrance, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering 6500 liquid gallons of regular unleaded gasoline to a customer location. The customer gave the driver a veeder root reading of 2420. Driver stuck the tanks and then again asked for the veeder root reading and was told the veeder root was out of paper but the reading measured 2420. Driver began to unload, when finished driver shut off flow to unloading head but approximately 4-6 gallons spilled from the drop. The spill was contained on concrete and no product was released into drains or soil. Upon invetigation by the Terminal Manager it was found the veeder root reading given was wrong, it should have been 4220.
column169: Driver was counseled/re-trained on the importance and necessity of verifying readings prior to unloading. Customer was made aware that 90% overfill valve was not working properly. Customer also made aware of wrong veeder root reading.

Parties Notified:  Florida Dept of Environmental Protection - Hassan Al-Buhaisi  Martin County Fire Department  Cliff Berry, Inc - John Katzor  State Warning Point  Zurich North America
column169: Customer Equipment Failure.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc Driver was delivering regular unleaded gasoline to a customer location. While unloading product the flow stopped. Driver waited for line to drain but nothing happened. Driver unlocked fitting and attempted to vent the line however there was pressure built up in the hose so the fuel left in the hose, approximately 5-10 gallons, spilled out onto the cement. The product was completely contained on concrete, not reaching soil or drains. The spill was cleaned up with spill pads, foam and water.
column169: Proper unloading procedures were reviewed with Driver. All safety meetings for the month of June will focus on spill prevention.

column168: The driver released 5-10 gallons of premium product at the station.    Driver reported that he had released 5 gallons of premium product at a station he was delivering to. The station is located at 501 E. Atlantic Blvd. Pompano  Beach, Fl. He stated that he had contained the product and had cleaned it up using his spill pads. Eagle management instructed him to contact Motiva Scheduling and report it to them, which he did and received a release #1-2347087891  from Harding. He also stated the reason for the release was because he misread the polecat and thought the product would fit.     Eagle Management met with the store owner and inspected the area around the drop site and found standing product in the expansion joints of the concrete pad. We spread kitty litter which soaked that up. We inspected a storm drain that was in the path of the release and found no product had reached it. We also inspected three monitoring wells and they did not show evidence of product in them.  The station owner requested that Eagle send someone to clean the drop basin so I notified Kim Lastrapes our mechanic who brought the equipment needed to complete the cleanup. He arrived at 09:50 and cleaned the kitty litter up along with the catch basins. He left the station after the station owner was satisfied with the work that was done.    Notified:   Florida DEP (Report #3264)  Motiva    No environmental issues.
column169: Better training on reading the polecat.

column168: A UPS DRIVER SERVICE PROVIDER SMELLED SMOKE IN THE CARGO AREA OF THE DELIVERY VEHICLE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY REMOVED THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE DID NOT BURN OR CAUSE OTHER DAMAGE. INVESTIGATION OF THE CONTENTS SHOWED THAT THE 30 LITHIUM BATTERIES WERE CONTAINED WITHIN THE PACKAGE AND THAT SOME OF THEM HAD SHORT CIRCUITED. UPS IS UNABLE TO DETERMINE THE LITHIUM CONTENT OF THESE BATTERIES. SEE ACCOMPANYING PHOTOGRAPHS.
column169: THE SHIPPER USED A PLASTIC TRAY TO HOLD THE BATTERIES, BUT IT CLEARLY DID NOT PROVIDE SUFFICIENT PROTECTION AGAINST SHORT CIRCUIT.IMPROVED SHORT CIRCUIT PROTECTION IS NEEDED.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported TOTX 1020 in the railyard dripping product down its side shell and TOTX 1020 was isolated in the railyard with catch buckets placed under it to catch any drips. No product ground impact was evident. BNSF responders reported finding the liquid eduction threaded Jamesbury ball valve in the closed position, but the closure plug was 1/2 turn less than tool tight. The loose plug was tool tightened and the product release ended.  Internal pressure inside TOTX 1020 was reduced. The product outage was checked and it was deemed appropriate. All spillage evaporated. Non-leaking TOTX 1020 was returned to the shipper origin location for detailed inspection of this Jamesbury ball valve.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman inspecting railcars in an outbound BNSF train in the railyard, reported product odor emanating from entrained SHPX 207153. A BNSF mechanical-hazardous material responder immediately inspected SHPX 207153. The responder reported the protective housing cover not sealed. The 75 psi external pressure relief device (PRD) had a pressure test needle valve at its base that was partially open and its closure plug was not applied. The responder closed this valve and applied the closure plug which ended any further vapor release by 0445 hrs. CDT, 5/20/07.  A small amount of liquid product was found near this open valve and it was evaporating. No product impacted the ground. Protective valve housing cover was sealed with numbered seal BNSF 002429.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

According to the information obtained the following occurred. While unloading approximately 2 ounces of product was discovered spilled on the truck onto the steel drums. column168: Driver was relaying a loaded cargo tank at our facility a few miles from the shipper.  When he stopped at the facility, he noticed some product in the crash box and it had started to drip down drain tube.  It appeared there was a problem with the dome gasket.  We contacted a spill response company to clean up what got on the ground and in the crash box. There didn't appear to be any leakage outside our facility.  Driver had stopped at truck stop and had done tire checks and didn't notice any leaks.  Leaky dome was fixed and load was delivered without further incident.
column169: A better pretrip inspection of the gaskets and vents on dome may have caught the problem.

column168: A BNSF switchman reported product odor emanating from residue methyl acrylate tank cars GLNX 3038 and GLNX 3039 in the railyard. These two tank cars were coupled together. BNSF contract responders inspected both of these tank cars. GLNX 3038 was found to be secure and not the odor source. GLNX 3039 was found with the liquid valve partially open 1/8 turn and vapors hissing through the loose closure plug for this valve. Responders closed the valve, which ended the vapor release and removed the loose plug. The plug threads were taped with Teflon. The closure plug was then reinserted and tool tightened. Securement was completed by 1530 hrs. CDT, 5/30/07.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: When material handler was unloading freight from trailer he discovered two pails that were slightly leaking from the top closures. Further investigation revealed that these pails were stretchwrapped to a pallet that had a 55 gallon drum staged in the middle of it. Apparently, while in transit the pails must have been slightly moving up and down and rubbing up against the 55 gallon drum that they were next to. As a result the chimes on the drum worked the lids loose on the two pails contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged pails.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: A drum of Nickel Chloride NI-Cl -/55 was delivered to Metro Plating in Mesa AZ.  The poly drum was on a drum dolly and was being moved over the edge of the driveway onto the customer site when it bounced up a bit when going over the driveway edge and one of the dolly's feet put a small hole about 1/4" x 1" in size in the bottom of the drum.  The drum was immediately placed on its side and moved onto the customer site. The duration of teh spill lasted approxamately 20 seconds. The spilled liquid was absorbed by absorbent from the driver's spill kit on the truck.  Two more Univar employees were sent to the site to assist in the final clean up.  The customer wanted to keep the drum and was able to use the material.
column169: The drum should have been wheeled, on the drum dolly, to the lip of the customer's driveway and set down on the street side.  Then the dolly should have been brought around to the driveway side and the drum picked up with the dolly and wheeled to the customer.  The process should have been completed using a two-step process instead of a one-step process.  This information and training was given to all Phoenix Univar drivers in a meeting on June 7th 2007.

column168: The drum that leaked was shipped from Amgen by Vilar Trucking on 5/3/2007 to the Veolia, Puerto Rico 10-day intransit facility.  The drum was then transported over the ocean on 5/7/2007 by Crowley Liner Services to the Port of Philadelphia.  The trailer was then transported on 5/23/2007 by Environmental Transport Group Inc. and delivered to the Veolia TSDF located in Flanders, NJ on 5/25/2007.    When the drum was off-loaded by Veolia receiving employees, it was identified as bulged and completely empty.  There was approximately <1 gallon of material residue on the floor of the trailer around the drum that required cleaning.  An investigation determined that the drum was shipped from Puerto Rico containing 55 gallons of waste material.  We believe pressure built up during transportation due to temperature change which caused the drum to develop a hole and leak the entire contents of the drum.  All leaked material must have then evaporated while in transit.    This spill was also reported to the NRC as required for a hazardous substance spill.
column169: Complete more thorough inspections of drums prior to shipping.

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: NECR switch crew #501 was switching cars in Italy yard.  The conductor tied a hand brake on car ACFX 200359 and the engineer pushed it approximately 5 car lengths to a stop as the cdr. walked along side the car.  The cdr. then had the engineer push on the car, and cut the car off from the movement.  The car sat momentarily on the yard track and then began to roll in a northward direction.  The cdr. reboarded the car and attempted to tighten the handbrake to no avail.  He then dismounted from the car and asked the engineer to come ahead and try to "catch" the car.  The car was rolling down a .07 grade and the train was unable to catch up with it.  It subsequently derailed on the derailing device that protects the main track at the north end of the yard.  The tank car rolled onto it's side.  The cdr. and a car department supervisor rushed to the scene with empty fuel cans and began to catch a small stream of diesel fuel that was coming from the vent valve on top of the railcar.  The train dispatcher was notified via emergency radio communication and he subsequently nofitied the St. Albans Fire Dept. and The State Of Vermont Environmental Dept.  R. J. Corman Rerailing Services came in and rerailed the car between 7:00PM and midnight.  The tank car was not breached in anyway.  The safety devices were repaired on the railcar and it was sent to it's final destination for unloading.  After unloading, it will be sent to it's "Home Shop" for final repairs.  Upon inspection by the mechanical department, a broken weld on the slack adjuster for the brake system was found on this car.  This allowed excessive piston travel and made the braking system ineffective.
column169: The employee involved in the incident is scheduled for a hearing.  Pending the outcome of the hearing and the facts that materialize, training concerning brake operation, inspection, and testing and possibly discipline will be assesed.

column168: Upon arrival of AA flight 605 into San Juan (SJU) on the night of May 11, 2007, the Fleet Service Clerks noticed a bag was "smoking" when they moved it to off load it in the cargo hold of the aircraft.  Per procedure, they exited the cargo compartment and alerted their Supervisor.  The Supervisor contacted the Lead Environmental Coordinator who responded from her home.  Upon arrival and inspecting the scene, she noticed a smell.  She commented that it smelled like muratic acid.    The roll-aboard type bag was removed from the aircraft and opened for inspection.  Inside were 19 bottles of product.  The bottles were labeled; Barnacle Cleaner, All Purpose Degreaser and Cleaner,  Step 2, Step 3 and Sealer.    The passenger had connected on to another flight.  The Lead Environmental Coordinator took possession of the bag and its contents to keep for FAA inspection and the FAA Hazmat office in SJU was advised.    An AA Aircraft Maintenance Supervisor removed a floorboard where the bag had been sitting and a sidewall panel since the bag had also been against that area.  An inspection was performed of the insulation blankets below the floor board and behind the sidewall panel and no evidence of acid was found.  The Supervisor treated the floorboard and panel with baking soda and reinstalled them.  The aircraft was returned to service.    Upon the return flight of the customer, further contact information was obtained to provide to the FAA Hazmat Inspector.  American Airlines Dangerous Goods Compliance and Maintenance and Engineering were both trying to obtain the MSDS (sheets) for the chemicals in the bag.  We were unsuccessful until we were finally able to contact the customer in Fort Lauderdale (FLL) several days later.  The MSDS (sheets) the customer faxed indicated that the Barnacle Remover contained Rust X which contained Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Inorganic, n.o.s., 8, UN3264, PG III, (Hydrochloric Acid) Cleaning Compound.    Although the Barnacle Remover product did not indicate any of this on the label, the instructions included a warning that said, "Do not use on soft metals, such as aluminum."    FAA Hazmat Inspector John Connally from the SJU office visited the Lead Environmental Coordinator at SJU Airport and obtained all the necessary information.    This event was also reported by American Airlines Dangerous Goods Compliance to the Southwest Region FAA Hazmat Office in Fort Worth, Texas.
column169: The TSA allowed this through in FLL.  It did NOT have any markings on it to indicate that it contained Hazmat.  Perhaps a name like Barnacle Cleaner would indicate that it is a fairly strong substance.  This might be one "trigger" to the agents that something is not correct.  The second "trigger" is that there were 19 Quart bottles in a soft sided roll aboard bag which is not normal and should maybe be questionable in today's environment.  We need to question more.  Had the TSA contacted someone in FLL it is pretty certain that the airline would have questioned the customer and perhaps avoided the incident.    There cannot be enough public outreach on many levels.  Perhaps print ads in newspapers and commercials on TV would help educate more people that don't want to read or listen to instructions at the airport.

column168: On 05/27/08 at 18:50 hrs., CSXT Mechanical Department discovered tank car ACFX 79908, load Methanol, leaking from the bottom outlet. The car was isolated and CSXT emergency response contractor, Veiolia Environmental, was contacted to respond. Train Master Chris Stevens climbed the rail car and turned the top operated bottom outlet valve handle one full handle to stop the leak, while waiting for Veiolia Envirnomental to arrive on the scene. Once on scene, Veiolia tightened the packing gland nut at the base of the top operated bottom outlet valve one full turn to secure the valve. Veiolia then went to the bottom outlet cap and tightened the cap one full turn to finish securing the car. Car was then released to destination.    Cause Code:  533  NARRI:  2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32

column168: Helena Chemical Company’s deliveiy truck departed its tenninal at one mile north on Wild Horse Road at approximately 0845 hours and was bound for a delivery at 202 Rehal, Joplin, MT. Its route took the vehicle through Havre, MT, on Main Street. The lading on board consisted of four pallets of various goods, three of which held five, 30 gallon containers, one held case packaged goods. Also loaded on the truck were two 120 gallon totes, a single  110 gallon tote and a single 30 gallon drum. The materials were loaded as shown on the attached diagram. Load securement bars were deployed as shown by the attached diagram.  At approximately 0900, while traveling westward on Main Street, the vehicle operator applied brakes sharply. The sudden braking caused the loaded material to shift forward. From the post-accident scene, it is believed that on braking, the 120 gallon tote loaded in 4th position-right shifted against the adjacent load bar causing the bar to fail. The tote slid forward and collided with the pallet of Weedmaster and the pallet jack. The pallet of Weedmaster and the ratchet load bar were dislodged, shifted leftward, and overturned. One of the 30 gallon drums was found to have been damaged on its head and the majority of its contents released (picture attached.)  No other release occurred. The cased goods in the pallet in first position-left were compressed but did not release. Packaging failure appears to be the result of a collision within the truck body of a 30 gallon HDPE drum with a protruding object, possibly the corner of a pallet.
column169: To prevent recurrence of incidents, drivers and warehouse personnel will review and refresh their knowledge of load securement. The FMCSA Driver’s Handbook on Cargo Securement will be reviewed.  Additional securement equipment will be purchased to supplement existing materials.  Driver’s will be re-trained on vehicle handling, including safe braking of vehicles and will be re-trained on the need for traffic situational awareness.

column168: An eastbound BNSF train being held for operational priority and parked in the siding at Somonauk, IL was reported by the local F.D. that an entrained tank car, MBLX 34129 (DOT 112J340W), was leaking product from a top fitting. All train traffic nearby was halted. BNSF contract responders inspected MBLX 34129, finding the A-end liquid valve partially open by 1/4 turn and its closure plug not applied. Responders closed this open valve and applied the closure plug, ending any further release prior to 0935 hrs. CDT, 5/18/07. Train traffic was allowed to resume at 0935 hrs. CDT, 5/18/07. Delays to three BNSF freight trains and two AMTRAK trains were incurred.    Per MBLX 34129's specification stencil, the tank qualification was 2005 by RELT, due 2015.

USES personnel utilized absorbents to contain the release and hand excavated the impacted soils.  All materials were containerized for transportation and disposal

column168: A cut of 34 loaded railcars rolled away downhill from a BNSF yard switch job's control. The cause of this roll-away was the crew's improper operation of train line air connections (bottling air) and the failure to apply handbrakes on these railcars. The lead three railcars rolled into a stopped yard switch consist in the railyard. The crew of this consist after being warned of the impending collision had stopped and secured the consist; then departed the area. The impact collision damaged and derailed both locomotives; and caused the trailing locomotive to derail into PLCX 220447 that was behind it. PLCX 220447 remained upright, but the impact resulted in a basketball sized puncture hole in the B-end tank head of PLCX 220447 at the lower left edge of the lower left quadrant of the tank head. The majority of the paving asphalt inside PLCX 220447 escaped through this puncture hole. BNSF environmental contractors excavated the spilled asphalt in the ground impact zone. Disposal of the excavated asphalt is pending. PLCX 220447 was deemed destroyed and its disposal is also pending.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On Thursday, May 3, 2007, Arnold Transportation notified A-C-T that a driver found a leaking drum of Polyester Resin Solution (UN1866, 3, III) in the trailer. Upon arrival at the site, the SUNPRO response team determined that there was an impacted area of 1-foot by 1-foot located in the middle of the trailer. The leak had occured from a puncture in the tp of the drum, but the response team was uable to determine the cause of the puncture. The drum was not leaking at the current time and granular sorbents had already been applied to the impacted area.  The response team overpacked the leaking drum into an 85-gallon overpack drum.  All sorbents were swept up into the overpack drum.  As per instructions from Arnold Transportation, the overpack drum was sealed and secured in the rear of the trailer for transportation to Arnold Transportation facility

column168: DURING A DAILY INSPECTION OF THE VEOLIA 10-DAY INTRANSIT FACILITY LOCATED IN PHILADELPHIA, PA, A LEAKING DRUM WAS DISCOVERED ON THE REAR OF ONE OF THE TEMPORARY STORAGE TRAILERS. THE DRUM HAD LEAKED ONTO THE SEALED PAVEMENT OF THE PARKING LOT AND WAS QUICKLY CONTAINED WITH SPEEDI DRI. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS THEN OVERPACKED INTO A STEEL OVERPACK WHICH WAS LABELED IN ACCORDANCE WITH DOT REQUIREMENTS.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE LEAKING DRUM IT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A 4 INCH GASH (HOLE) WHICH APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY A FORKLIFT WHEN THE DRUM WAS OFFLOADED FROM ONE OF THE SERVICE TRUCKS ONTO THE TRAILER. THE DRUM CONTAINED ALOT OF SPILL CLEANUP MATERIAL WHICH SLOWED THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL TO THE TRUCK AND GROUND. TOTAL LOSS OF MATERIAL WAS APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MINERAL SPIRITS. THE CONCENTRATION OF MINERAL SPIRITS IN THE CONTAINER WAS 1-5% PER THE WASTE INFORMATION PROFILE SHEET (WIP).
column169: VEOLIA WILL PROVIDE REFRESHER FORKLIFT TRAINING TO THE LOADING DOCK EMPLOYEES WHICH WILL ALSO COVER SITUATIONS WHEN USE OF A HAND CART IS PREFERRED.

column168: AA International flight 293 had arrived in Chicago (ORD) from Delhi (DEL), India.  The baggage was offloaded and transported to the TSA screening area prior to Customers claiming their baggage and clearing U.S. Customs.  The TSA was using a CTX machine when Mr. Schmidt's bag "alarmed" in the machine.  The TSA opened the bag and discovered a 3-4 oz plastic bottle containing liquid Mercury.  Due to the lower pressure in flight, the Mercury had expanded and leaked out of the bottle between the threads in the cap and the bottle contaminating Mr. Schmidt's personal effects inside the bag.      At this point in time, the extent of the spilled Mercury was inside Mr. Schmidt's bag.  The bag was confiscated by the TSA and tendered to American Airlines for reporting to the FAA.  The FAA Great Lakes Regional Hazmat office was notified.    Mr. Schmidt was notified that the Mercury had been detected by the TSA, had spilled in his bag and that is was Hazmat.  Mr. Schmidt replied that he is a photographer and uses the Mercury in his photographic process.  Mr. Schmidt was advised that his bag and its contents could not be returned to him as it was now a Hazardous waste.    American Airlines had an Environmental cleanup company respond after some of the Mercury was spilled during FAA inspection.  The bag and the Mercury was then disposed of by the Hazardous Waste disposal company as per procedure.
column169: Mercury is a special element in that it is liquid metal.  People may not realize its properties of expansion and contraction even though it is used in thermometers and barometers among other common things.    Special public outreach should be done to ensure more people understand that Mercury is poisonous, corrosive, has unusual properties depending upon its environment and is very harmful to humans and animals when allowed to leak out into the general environment.  Mercury is too easy for the general public to obtain and transport in ways that are not suitable.  Thus we must either restrict its availability or ensure more people understand the science of Mercury better.

The tanker was pumped out by Miller Environmental, righted, and towed back to Albany, NY, with no further release.

CAUSE-FOR-LOSS # 1178 WAS INPUT IN THE SITE CORRECTIVE ACTION SYSTEM FOR TRACKING INCIDENT CORRECTIVE ACTIONS AND FOLLOWUP. THIS WILL BE SHARED WITH ALL WEYERHAEUSER UNLOADING PERSONNEL. UNLOADING OPERATORS ARE EXPECTED TO CHECK ALL CAPS, NOT JUST LOOK AT SEALS.

column168: xAt 0015 hours, 05/31/2007, train Y39230 derailed at CSX Transportations Stanley Yard, Walbridge, OH. Seven (7) tank cars containing styrene monomer, inhibited were involved. Four tank cars, CGTX 26338, CGTX 26242, CGTX 26193 and PROX 23032 rolled approximately 90 onto their side. These four tank cars released material from their vacuum relief devices. CGTX 26338, CGTX 26193 and PROX 23032 released approximately 1 gallon each. CGTX 26242 released approximately 200 gallons. In addition, PROX 23032 released approximately 1 gallon from its gauge device, A Scully gague device. Leak was at the electrical connection faceplate. Eagle Construction and Environmental Services, Inc. (ECESI), Findlay, OH was dispatched. ECESI stopped leaks at vacuum relief devices using wooden shims. The tank cars were uprighted, rerailed and contaminated soil removed by ECESI. The seven tank cars were transferred  by ECESI into seven other tank cars at Stanley Yard. ECESI cleaned and purged the seven tank cars involved in the derailment. The tanks are to be loaded onto flat cars for transport to a tank car repair facility.

column168: RAIL CAR NO. PLCX221297 WAS RECEIVED IN FACILITY ON 05/26/07.  THE CAR WAS BEING OFF LOADED AND CONTAINED ACQ 2102, A WOOD PRESERVATIVE.  BEFORE OFF LOADING, THE ON DUTY OPERATOR INSPECTED THE RAIL CAR TO ENSURE THE BELLY VALUE WAS CLOSED & LOCKED IN THE "CLOSED" POSITION, WHICH IT WAS.  THE OPERATOR INITIATED REMOVAL OF THE BELLY VALVE PLUG IN ORDER TO MAKE HOSE CONNECTIONS.  WHILE UNSCREWING THE PLUG, THE PLUG BLEW OUT DUE TO PRESSURE.  APPROX.  5000 GALLONS WAS RELEASED.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT PRIOR TO RECEIVING THE CAR, THE CAR HAD BEEN WORKED ON BY ANOTHER WHO POSSIBLY INSTALLED THE BELLY VALVE HANDLE BACKWARDS CAUSING THE VALVE TO BE ACTUALLY "OPEN" WHEN IT WAS IN THE CLOGGED POSITION.  MOVING THE HANDLE TO THE OPEN POSITION ACTUALLY STOPPED THE FLOW.
column169: A U.S. DOT INVESTIGATION IS IN PROGRESS BY L. LEE HUTON, SAFETY INSPECTOR FOR THE U.S. DOT. INFORMATION IS BEING REGISTERED FROM THE ENTITY WHO MADE THE REPAIRS, WHICH WAS NOT NUSTAR ENERGY, L.P. THE FACILITY IS REQUIRING ALL FUTURE RAIL CARS HAVE A SECONDARY BACKUP VALVE INSTALLED BEFORE IT IS RECEIVED BY NUSTAR ENERGY, L.P.

column168: Lykins Transportation, Inc.   Incident Date: 5/23/2007   Rollover accident occurred 12:49 p.m. (according to police incident report). First call received into our dispatch center at 12:55 p.m. Our unit was traveling WB on I-74 and exiting at exit 11 via a 1/4 mile exit ramp with the intention of turning left on Harrison Ave. Response of our driver was that he had just came off I-74 and was off throttle and stab breaking the unit as he traveled the exit ramp (#11) off I-74 toward Harrison Ave. Driver said he was stab breaking the unit until his speed was down to 35 mph and that he then went into 7th gear. Then as unit continued slowing and with more stab breaking to get the unit down to 25 mph — at which point he took unit out of gear — that as unit slowed he pressed accelerator slightly as unit reached 15 mph and he shifted into 5th gear and turned onto Harrison Ave. Driver stated he was getting down to what he perceived to me a safe speed for the turn and also have the unit in a gear that would enable him to start the climb up the hill as he started up Harrison Ave. Driver stated as he entered into the actual turn that it felt as if the rear of the unit was lifting off the ground and he felt as if it was pushing into the turn. As the unit was in process of the turn onto Harrison Ave. it rolled over onto passenger side, top and then onto the driver’ side of unit — coming to rest on the “corner” of the driver’s side and top of unit. A passing motorist had observed the accident and had called 911 and then assisted our driver get out of the unit by breaking out the windshield and assisting driver out. Driver attempted to shut off the truck engine prior to getting out of unit and it would not shut off and per driver the engine ran for a short while after he was extracted from the cab of the unit. Driver stated as the motorist assisted him out of truck he noticed that fuel was coming, at a pretty strong stream, out of the hole that had been ruptured into the top side of barrel near top rail and that as the engine of the truck was still running the motorist insisted and assisted him to a safe place away from the unit and spilling fuel. The motorist advised driver he had called 911 and our driver called our dispatch office on his cell and advised of the rollover and product spill situation.   Our unit is a five (5)-compartment tank wagon fuel delivery truck. During the rollover the driver’s side top portion of aluminum barrel of tank portion of unit was impacted against the roadway and curb area of roadway and a 4-5” gouged hole was evident in the tank as noted. 1,130 gallons, 96% of the 1,355 gallons of spilled product, came out of the “hole” in the #1 compartment. The dome lids of Compartment # 1 and Compartment #2 appeared to be loosened from the impact of the rollover and product seepage of approx. 225 gallons escaped from compartment #2 as well.   The majority of the product spillage, out of compartment # 1, from the unit more than likely occurred

column168: ON 5/22/2007, I WAS CONTACTED BY TELEPHONE BY OUR MIAMI, FLORIDA AGENT-GILBERT ARZA. HE INFORMED ME THAT ONE OF OUR DRIVERS HAD DELIVERED AN INTER-MODAL CONTAINER TO THE CONSIGNEE. UPON BEING OPENED AND UN-LOADED BY THE CONSIGNEE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE INTER-MODAL CONTAINER CONTAINED APPROX. (14) FOUR-TEEN DRUMS THAT WERE LABELED WITH CLASS 3/FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABELS. THROUGH FURTHER INVESTIGATION/INQUIRY IT WAS LEARNED THAT OUR DRIVER J. BANUS (UNIT # 750-002) HAD PICKED UP AN INTER-MODAL CONTAINER/CHASSIS (# CSXV 986121) FROM F.E.C. RAILROAD (VIA CSX) 7600 N.W. 69TH AVE MEDLEY (MIAMI) FL 33178. DELIVERY WAS MADE TO THE CONSIGNEE-ECONOCARIBE CONSOLIDATORS 2401 N.W. 69TH ST. MIAMI, FL. THE DRUMS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS WERE DISCOVERED WHEN THE CONSIGNEE ENTERED THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER IN ORDER TO UN-LOAD THE CARGO.(CONTINUED SEE ADDITIONAL PAGES)

TRANSPORT WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON U.S. HIGHWAY 50.  THE HIGHWAY ENTERS A NARROW WINDING CANYON.  THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING TO FAST FOR THE SHARPNESS OF A CURVE AND ROLLED THE VEHICLE ONTO ITS SIDE.  AS THE VEHICLE SLID DOWN THE ROADWAY, THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK IMPACTED THE ROCK WALL OF THE CANYON.  A HOLE WAS PUNCTURED IN THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK-APP 1 1/2" TO 2" OPENING WAS CREATED ALLOWING THE BUTANE TO ESCAPE.  THE BUTANE VAPORIZED AS IT WAS NO LONGER UNDER PRESSURE AND DISSIPATED IN THE ATMOSHPERE.  FIRE DEPARTMENT & HIGHWAY PATROL EVACUATED NEARBY RESIDENTS AND CAMPGROUNDS, CLOSED THE HIGHWAY AND ALLOWED THE BUTANE TO DISSIPATE.  AFTER THE WRECKAGE WAS REMOVED TESTS WERE DONE TO MAKE SURE NO SOIL CONTAMINATION OCCURED.

column168: 5/19/07 -Shipment received from McElroy Manufacturing Inc. (“McElroy”) by Expeditors International of Washington, Inc. (“Expeditors”) in Grapevine, TX. McElroy did not declare the shipment as hazardous. The shipment was described as machinery. -The shipment was packaged as 3 skids covered in shrink-wrap. One of the skids contained a machine on wheels incorporating a fuel tank containing fuel. (see photo enclosed)  - Expeditors prepared the international airwaybill for shipment to Santiago Chile in accordance with McElroy’s instructions. - Expeditors arranged for delivery of the shipment to the exporting carrier, American Airlines. -Upon delivery to American Airlines, the receiving agent discovered a fuel tank attached to a machine on wheels which was covered by plastic shrink-wrap. -The shipment was returned to Expeditors facility in Grapevine. 5/21/07 Expeditors contacted McElroy to resolve the undeclared hazmat issue. 5/22/07 McElroy arranged to have the shipment repackaged and documented as Dangerous Goods.
column169: As follow-up to this incident, Expeditors Tulsa branch manager requested a meeting with a representative of McElroy. Mr. Mike Vaughn, General Accounting Manager of McElroy has agreed to the meeting which is scheduled for June 21st, 2007. The purpose of the meeting is to discuss the incident, and the seriousness of complying with hazmat regulations. The attached Expeditors informational series document on shipping dangerous goods will also be discussed. May 30, 2007 Expeditors delivered reinforcement general awareness training to its employees involved in processing shipments. This training emphasized the importance of closely reviewing documentation and cargo for any signs of hidden dangerous goods.

column42: VEHICLE, FLAMMABLE GAS POWERED OR VEHICLE, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE GAS POWERED
column168: 5/18/07 -Shipment received from Carrington Laboratories inc. (“Carrington”) by Expeditors International of Washington, Inc. (“Expeditors”) in Grapevine, TX.   - Carrington offered the shipment as non-hazardous (see enclosed shipper’s letter of instruction). - The shipment was packaged as 1 skid containing 12 cartons covered in plastic shrink-wrap + 2 loose cartons. 5/19/07 - Expeditors prepared the international airwaybill for shipment to San Jose Costa Rica in accordance with Carrington’s instructions. - Expeditors arranged for delivery of the shipment to the exporting carrier, American Airlines. - Upon delivery to American Airlines, the receiving agent examined boxes that were covered by shrink-wrap and found a package with UN markings embedded with the other cartons on the skid and refused the shipment. -The shipment was returned to Expeditors facility in Grapevine. 5/21/07   - Expeditors contacted Carrington to question the package marked with UN markings and one line item on the commercial invoice described as Potassium Permanganate.   - Carrington responded that they were unaware the carton contained dangerous goods.   - Carrington provided a revised commercial invoice removing the items contained in the package with UN Markings (including the Potassium Permanganate) and asked Expeditors to return that package to Carrington and forward the remaining packages in the shipment to its customer in Costa Rica.
column169: As follow-up, Expeditors export manager met with Lonnie Wells, Transportation Director for Carrington Laboratories, Inc. to discuss the incident and highlighted the dangers of shipping undeclared dangerous goods, both to the environment, people, property, and the consequences involved. Mr. Wells said that he would relay these points to his shipping staff and incorporate them in follow-up training. As corrective action, Mr. Wells. stated his team will begin to inspect each carton and also isolate the dangerous goods so that each carton can be inspected before the shipment is offered. As a remedial measure, on May 30, 2007 Expeditors held a meeting with its employees involved in processing or handling shipments to discuss this incident and emphasized the importance of closely reviewing documentation and cargo for any signs of hidden dangerous goods. Expeditors has also setup a procedure internally whereby any shipment received from Carrington will be inspected, carton by carton, by a lead, supervisor, or manager.

column168: On May 31, 2007, Product Distribution Company contracted to transport a trailer-load of equipment from GE Lighting in Atlanta, GA, to GE Lighting in Charleston, TN.  The load included forklift batteries which contain about 50 gallons of acid and water solution.  The batteries were attached to wooden pallets with plastic strap banding.  At about 10 pm that night, the driver, Barry Guider, stopped for fuel at the Penske Truck Leasing facility in Chattanooga, TN.  He noticed a liquid dripping from the trailer doors and smelled battery acid.  The pallet holding the battery crushed, causing the support straps to become loose, which resulted in the battery tipping and knocking against something that cause the battery case to crack and about 2.5 gallons of sulfuric acid to leak out.  He contacted his dispatcher, who directed him to continue and complete his scheduled delivery.  He was about 50 miles away from the receiving facility.  Upon arrival, he notified the receiving facility of the spill, and was directed where to drop his trailer.  He was told they would neutralize the spill and clean it up.  The receiving facility cleaned and neutralized the trailer upon notification by the driver.
column169: 1) Implement additional job function training for the drivers to recognize potential hazardous material for transportation and then not to accept any hazardous material for transport. They will also be trained to understand their roles and responsibilities during a potential incident on the road which will include notifying the dispatcher and management to receive directions on proper spill response and clean up.  The dispatcher will receive training on steps needed to be taken to collect information from the driver and how to escalate the incident to management.    2) Shipper has been contacted and informed of the incident. Shipper informed us that they have developed procedures for shipping wet acid batteries, using more substantial pallets and strapping.    3) Implement additional training for drivers on identification of proper securing, locking and bracing of loads per 49 CFR 392.9.

column168: On May 23, 2007 at 17:25 the transport left the Heath, OH Terminal, owned by Marathon Petroleum Company, with a load of gasoline and diesel fuel. The delivery was for Speedway #9312 located at 117 East Main Street Newark, OH. The transport was traveling north on Cherry Valley Road in Newark, OH when the driver failed to negotiate a curve in the road. The transport left the road and over turned into Raccoon Creek. The transport caught fire and burned for approximately three hours. The local emergency responders responded to the accident, fire, police, and EMS. Public Utilities Commission of Ohio, EPA, and local emergency management also responded. Marathon Petroleum Company was not notified immediately because the fire prevented identifying the transport. Marathon responders arrived on scene at approximately 20:30. The tractor and trailer were a total loss. The trailer was lying on the right side with left side being burned away so the actual tank failure is unknown. Most of the product burned away with very little traveling down Raccoon Creek. BBU, Environmental Contractor, responded by placing containment boom in Raccoon Creek at two downstream locations and two at the accident site. Some product was recovered down stream at a boom site and the product that remained in the transport was vacuumed into a truck. The tractor and trailer were removed from the creek on 5/24/07 around 15:00 with very little environmental impact.

column168: ON 05/04/07, TANK CAR UTLX 666623, LOAD OF PHENOL, WAS FOUND LEAKING DURING SWITHING OPERATIONS AT PENSACOLA, FL.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, SWS, WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL, SWS FOUND THE CAR LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY DUE TO ONE BOLT BEING LEFT LOOSE, AND THE GASKET WAS NOT MAKING CONTACT ALL THE WAY AROUND THE MANWAY. SWS INSTALLED A NEW GASKET AND SECURED THE BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT AND LEAK STOPPED.  CARE RELEASSED TO FINAL DESTINATION. CAUSE CODE: 200 NARRI: 5(5+5+0)X(2+0)=100
column169: NO ADDITIONAL COMMENTS.

column168: DRIVER MADE CONNECTIONS FROM THE TRAILER TO STORAGE TANK WITH 2" HOSE. ONCE THE UNLOADING PROCESS WAS STARTED THE DRIVER NOTICE A LEAK IN THE HOSE. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE UNLOADING PROCESS AND DRAINED HOSE IN A BUCKET. THE DRIVER SWITCHED OUT THE BAD HOSE, RECONNECTED AND FINISHED THE UNLOADING. THE DAMAGED HOSE LEAK LESS THAN I GALLON OF PRODUCT IN THE DIKED AREA AND WAS CLEANED UP BY THE DRIVER AND THE UNLOADEDER. THE DAMAGED HOSE HAD A PUNCTURE APPROXIMATELY 18" FROM COUPLER WERE IT APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN BENT AT ONE TIME.
column169: CONSIGNEES SHOULD SUPPLY THERE OWN HOSES SPECIFIC TO THERE PRODUCTS. DRIVERS WERE PROVIDED REFRESHER TRAIING ON VISUAL DELIVERY EQUIPMENT INSPECTION.

column168: Plant operator connected their unload hose to our trailer, vented our trailer, started their pump, opened the unload valves and then notices a small drip coming from the 3 x 2 bushing on the discharge side of our external valve.  Operator shut down to inspect and found bushing was corroded.  Bushing was immediately replaced and the load was delivered without further incident.
column169: We have asked our mechanics to visually check all fittings during normal PM's and if they see any sign of corrosion, cracking or abraded areas, the fitting is to be replaced immediately.

column168: While driver was enroute, he noticed product leaking from the rupture disc drain hose.  He immediately pulled off the road.  Mechanic was called to the scene to make repairs.  Driver continued on and made delivery without further incident.
column169: We were unable to determine if the rupture disc burst due to pressure or liquid splashing up onto the material.  This was a shipper trailer that we had pulled for a couple of days.  After this incident, it was returned to the shipper so we do not know what they did.  However, our trailers are similar and we instructed all of our drivers never to over pressurize the vessel to the point the rupture disc could blow and if that happened to let dispatch know immediately so repairs could be made prior to its next dispatch.

column168: • 5-21-2007:   Routine pickup of Kodak waste drum (profile #KODAKWA-02) with drum liner and SM kit (plastic containers with residue of photo chemicals); PSC employee James Lindholm at Target #1868 Sherwood, OR between 3pm and 4pm.   • 5-22-2007:  9AM James reports missing drum to Pat Hymas at start of off-loading at Washougal. The drum may have fallen out during transport because he recalls having to pull over to re-close the side door of his truck the previous day after the Target pick up.  It is determined through surveillance video that the drum came out of the vehicle in the parking lot. Drum was not on the grounds at that time.  • 5-23-2007:   Pat reported incident to PSC Regulatory Affairs Mike Sheehan and Keith Lund. Pat was instructed to contact and report incident to National Response Center and the local Fire Dept. NRC report # 836294.  • 5-24-2007:   Pat goes to Target store. After speaking with the manager Pat decided to look around property. The blue barrel was in the dumpster containment. Drum was picked up that afternoon, with original paperwork, and delivered to the Washougal facility.  • 5-25-2007:  Pat is informed by the driver that the drum is in fact empty. Pat then returns to the store but the garbage had been dumped recently. No drum liner or the SM kit was found.
column169: Employee was retrained on securing loads and was reprimanded.

column168: of the release, if possible Describe what was done to mitigate the effects of the release. Continue on additional sheets if  Upon arrival of Midwest Airlines flight 809 from Milwaukee, WI, personnel unloading the aircraft noticed 5 boxes of a cargo shipment appeared wet and 1 had broken open. There was a liquid substance on the floor of the aircraft cargo compartment. Persoirnel working the flight indicated the substance had an odor similar to finger nail polish. Several small bottles appeared to have damaged caps. The airport fire department was contacted to conduct an evaluation of the material. The shipper was contacted and an MSDS for the spilled product was obtained. Airport fire personnel reviewed the MSDS and allowed cleanup to proceed. Maintenance inspection of the aircraft was conducted and the aircraft returned to service with a delay of approximately 2 hours and 45 minutes. The FAA Hazardous Materials Regional Office with authority for Las Vegas was notified by telephone as per 49CFR 175.31.  The boxes in quesiion contained no external indication that the contents were hazardous material or a description of the contents. Shipper failed to declare the contents as hazardous material and acknowledged on shipping documentation that the shipment did not contain hazardous materials.

Quayne Day, Yardmaster, reported a release of product from the top of Tankcar GATX 22609, at the east hump of the North Platte Yard at Mile Post 290.84. Mr. Day stated there were no fires, no injuries, no exposures, and no danger of the product entering into any waterways. Kim Keeling, Manager of Environmental Field Services, was notified and responded. Necessary state notifications were made. At 08:38 PM, Mgr. Keeling confirmed one employee was exposed to fumes. Federal notification was made. At 09:30 PM, Quayne Day, Yardmaster, advised a second employee was exposed to fumes from the release, both employees declined medical treatment and were sent home. At 11:16 PM, Mr. Keeling advised the tankcar was returned to service and advised the release occurred from the top manway cover. Mr. Keeling further advised a temporary gasket had been placed in the tankcar until it arrived at its destination. No further remediation was conducted.

column169: THIS WILL BE A FUTURE TOPIC OF DISCUSION DURING PRESHIFTS WITH OUR DRIVERS. column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.
