column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT  OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE  COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. APPROIPRIATE DISCIPLINE WAS ISSUED.

column168: 1 At 08:45am a Clean Harbors employee reported to myself that there had been a small spill in the back of a box truck that she hadj been off-loading onto the outbound trailers when she noticed that one of the 5 gallon carboy had a bit of a residue on outsidecontainer with slight odor and was slightly bulging. It had also oxidized the floor board and the cardboard copak box next to it. Afterdonning a repirator and tyvek I inspected the container and noticed that according to the Haz Waste label from the Generator that itwas a solution of 15% Nitric Acid, 8% Hydrochloric acid, remaining water. After examining the container it was determined to beRed Fuming Nitric Acid due to the positive oxidizer test, red staining of carboy, and fume generation when carboy was moved. TheGenerator (Roche Palo Alto LLC) was notified of having misidentified their waste and the manifest was adjusted and the carboy waspacked per DOT-SP-13192 and added to the manifest. Originally manifested on Line # 1 and Remanifested to Line 14. See1 attached Generator Label and corrected manifest.

column168: TANK CAR TILX 190378 WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BY A SWITCH CREW. THE RATE OF RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY A DRIP EVERY 3 SECONDS. MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CAR, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO AN OPEN BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT VALVE CAP. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, THE VALVE HANDLE PINNED. THE VALVE CAP TIGHTENED ONE HALF TURN, AND THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD RELEASED APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT. NO REMEDIATION WAS DEEMED NECESSARY AS THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS CAPTURED IN A BUCKET.

column168: Dean Cooper, Manager, Hazardous Materials, reported dried product had been observed on both sides of tank car GATX 22276, which was located on the Rip Track, Bakersfield, CA. Mr. Cooper stated the dried product was confined solely to the top portion and sides of the railcar, and no product was observed on the ground. At 11:22AM, Manager Cooper advised the cause of the product release was three loose manway swing bolts, allowing product release from the left side of the manway nozzle. Manager Cooper further stated the loose bolts allowed product surge to blow out the left side of the gasket from between the nozzle and the manway cover plate. The inverted ‘J’ type gasket was so badly distorted, it had lobe replaced with a standard flat manway gasket. After the manway was secured, ACTI Environmental cleaned the dried residue from the surface of the tank car. The tank car was then released for movement onto the consignee.

column168: Dean Cooper, Manager, Hazardous Materials, reported he received a notification from the Mechanical Department of a leaking tank car at Bakersfield, CA. Mr. Cooper advised tank car GATX 22252 released approximately twenty gallons of product, which had solidified on the top and side portions of the tank car. The tank car was set to the rip track and secured. Mr. Cooper further advised upon investigation the release occurred from a bad manway gasket. Noted were three of the eight manway swing bolts unsecured and hanging down. The unsecured manway bolts allowed the product surge to blow out a portion of the manway gasket, which sprayed the top of the tank car, and a portion of a second tank car, UTLX 66140, that was coupled into the tank. The inverted ‘J’ style nianway gasket was so badly distorted; it had to be replaced with standard flat manway gasket. After properly securing the swing bolts, ACTI Environmental cleaned the residue from both tank cars. The tank cars were then released for movement onto the consignee.

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURED WHEN ARCTIC EXPRESS HAD A TRACTOR/TRAILER ACCIDENT DURING SNOWY CONDITIONS. ARCTIC EXPRESS UTILIZED A LOCAL CLEANUP CREW TO AID IN THE RECOVERY OF THE CARGO. ONCE THE CARTO HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE WRECKED TRAILER IT WAS INSPECTED OVERPACKED AND PLACED INTO ANOTHER ARCTIC EXPRESS TRAILER AND SENT ON FOR REDELIVER. THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED THE SHIPMENT. ARCTIC EXPRESS THEN HAD THE LOAD OF REJECTED CARGO TRANSPORTED TO A DROP YARD IN SALT LAKE CITY, UT PENDING REPROCESSING. WHILE THE TRAILER SAT WAITING FOR A DECISION TO HAVE THE MATERIAL RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURE FOR REPROCESSING OR SENT TO FOR DISPOSAL, ONE DRUM BEGAN TO LEAK. MR. KETTMAN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT COORDINATED WITH TW COMPANY TO INSPECT THE TRAILER AND CARGO AND CORRECT THE LEAK. THE CREW NOTED THE PREVIOUS CLEANUP CONTRACTOR NOT TWO COMPANY HAD PLACED A 55 GALLON DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID INTO A METAL 85 GALLON OVERPACK. THE LEAKING DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID HAD A TEAR IN THE BOTTOM SIDEWALL FROM ACCIDENT. THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO THE OVERPACK WITH THE SIDEWALL TEAR DOWN WHICH ALLOWED THE ADDITIONAL SULFURIC ACID TO BE RELEASED INTO THE METAL DRUM. THIS RELEASED ACID ATE THROUGH THE METAL OVERPACK CAUSING THE RELEASE. THE CREW PLACED THE LEAKING POLY DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID AND THE METAL OVERPACK INTO A 95 GALLON POLY OVERPACK. THE POLY 95 GALLON OVERPACK IS A COMPATABLE CONTAINER TO CONAIN THE SULFURIC ACID. THE TW CREW ESTIMATED THE 55 GALLON POLY DRUM HAD LOST AN ESTIMATED 25 GALLONS TO THE 85 GALLON METAL OVERPACK AND TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.

column168: On May 15, immediately upon notification of the spill, we contacted SWS Environmental First Response, P.O. Box 15459, Panama City, FL 32406-5459 and employed the company for remediation purposes. Their personnel arrived on site shortly afterwards and were entirely in charge of the cleanup activity. After completion of their work, personnel from the GA EPD and the site supervisor examined the area and deemed the cleanup to have been completed.    Saraguay Petroleum received an extensive report from SWS Environmental detailing their work and providing job site photos, logs, waste manifest, and test results of samples to confirm removal of the product. This report is readily available should any questions remain after your review of the following.    At this time, and at the notification of SWS, we consider the file closed and the spill area cleaned and remediated to like conditions prior to the event. We have contacted the owners of the site and they too concur.  Particular matters of interest as indicated in your correspondence are provided on the following page.    1. The spilled product leached down from the spill site, a 12,000 gallon above ground storage tank. A minimal amount of product leached in to a storm drain and traveled through the piping network and collected in a retention pond at the bottom of the road.  2. The total amount of product spilled was 600-70+/- gallons of dyed diesel fuel. Product which reached the pond was estimated to be 50+- gallons.  3. The spill occurred around 4 PM on 5/15/07, was contained by 8 PM, and the clean up concluded on 5/18/07. Backfill of the excavated site and removal of the absorbent boom from the retention pond were completed on 5/25/07. A project log maintained by SWS is provided as an enclosure.  4. The spill was caused by a “stupid American who should have known better” driver who did not follow company policy requiring his immediate presence at the site of the drop. Instead, after he began pumping off the product, he went to sit in the cab of his truck and did not notice that the hose had disconnected from the delivery point and product was spilling. Every action the driver took after starting the pump was in violation of written company policy. He was terminated that very evening.  5. The retention pond is not named—it is we believe a relatively new feature there in conjunction with the construction project.  a. The distance from the spill site to the pond was 200+/- feet.  b. There were no downstream receiving waters affected.  c. The first major body of water in the vicinity, unaffected by the spill is Hickory Log Creek.  6. A Site location map is provided as an enclosure.  7. A drawing of the site is provided as an enclosure.  8. A sketch of the spill site showing the extent of the spill is provided as an enclosure.  9. As mentioned earlier, we have numerous digital photos of the spill, before and after the cleanup, provided by SWS Environmental and archived on 4 CDs. I contacted Mel Rechtman
column169: STOP HIRING STUPID AMERIANS AND HIRE SMARTER IMMIGRANTS.

column169: Inspections have been reiterated numerous times at our safety meetings and will continue to do so. The fourth quarter safety meeting will be devoted to pre-trip inspections, post trip inspections, en-route inspections and post loading inspection to include the slosh test of our equipment before leaving any shipper's facility.

column168: Our driver finished loading at the shipper, checked the top of his trailer for securement and started to leave the plant.  When he stopped at a railroad crossing within the confines of the facility, some product leaked out and down the drain tubes and again at the plant gate.  Investigation revealed the dome gasket was pinched when our driver closed the dome lid allowing the product to leak out.      The dome gasket was replaced with a new one which stopped the leak.  Plant personnel cleaned up the spilled product themselves.
column169: Drivers are taught to make sure the dome gasket is seated firmly in its groove to prevent it from being pinched by the lid when closing the dome.
column198: Enterprise Transportation Company a division of EPCO, INC.

column168: Driver had a blow-out on the tractor on US 93, at mile post 139.  He pulled over to the side of the road and unhooked his trailer so repairs could be made.  When he moved from under the trailer he did not notice that the shoulder was soft and the trailer tipped over on it side, causing the product to fall and the drums containing the hazardous material ruptured.  The doors of the trailer came open and the hazardous material came out of the door onto the ground.  The Arizona State Police were called to the scene and, after examining the crash site, called for a hazardous material cleanup team.  The cleanup team was able to contain the spill, neutralize the effect of the material that was spilled and clean up all the spilled material within a twenty-four period.
column169: In an effort to not have this situation again, the drivers of this fleet were retrained on the aspect of emergency road service procedures, the inspection of load securement, the determination of safe parking sites and proper Pre-trip inspection techniques.  A suggestion for all transportation elements in all states would be to make sure that those areas that have soft shoulders be marked with the appropriate signage to warn the driving public of this possible hazard.
